  "note": "ARCH-11 shared golden vectors for the MCP-server-entry drift guard. Both @ax/sandbox-protocol's McpServerSchema (the host contract) and @ax/agent-claude-sdk-runner's hand-rolled validateMcpEntry (sandbox-side defense-in-depth, intentionally NOT importing the schema) are asserted against THIS one file. Each vector declares its expected verdict PER SIDE: `schema` (McpServerSchema.safeParse(.value).success) and `runner` (validateMcpEntry(.value) returns vs throws). `core: true` vectors test the security-critical shape rules that MUST NEVER diverge — both sides assert schema === runner for those. TASK-18 CLOSED ASYMMETRY (b): McpServerSchema now caps env to <=32 entries and <=256-char keys/values, matching validateMcpEntry (and the upstream @ax/skills-parser manifest parser), so the three env-oversize vectors are now SYMMETRIC (both reject) and promoted to core. The ONE remaining `core: false` vector encodes the surviving intentional asymmetry (a): the runner ignores allowedHosts/credentials (it only emits name/transport/command/args/env/url into .mcp.json), so a value the schema rejects PURELY on a malformed allowedHosts/credentials field is still accepted by the runner. That direction (schema rejects, runner accepts) is benign here precisely because the runner discards those fields — it cannot smuggle anything through them. If either validator flips a verdict on any vector, one of the two drift suites fails -> CI red, forcing a conscious fixture + cross-reference update. Note: every vector includes allowedHosts/credentials so McpServerSchema sees them explicitly; the runner ignores them either way.",
